Region pairs in Azure refer to two geographically connected Azure regions within the same geography that are linked together for disaster recovery and data replication purposes. Microsoft ensures that each region is paired with another region located hundreds of miles away to reduce the risk of simultaneous failure.

For example, Central India is paired with South India. If one region experiences an outage due to natural disasters, power failure, or network issues, services can failover to the paired region.

A real-life use case is a banking system storing critical financial data. The bank can replicate its databases from one region to its paired region, ensuring that even in case of failure, no data is lost and services remain operational.

Another example is enterprise applications that require high availability. By leveraging region pairs, organizations can design robust disaster recovery strategies without manually managing multiple locations.

Region pairing is a foundational concept for business continuity planning in Azure.
